In React, login state automatically continues across new tabs if you store the auth/session correctly.
A new tab reloads the app, so state in memory (React state, Redux store) is lost.
You must persist authentication outside React memory.
Below are correct, production‑ready approaches, from most common to best practice.

✅ What you actually want
	If user is already logged in, opening a new tab should keep them logged in
This is achieved by persisted authentication + rehydration on app load.

✅ Best & Most Common Solutions
✅ 1. Use Cookies (HTTP‑only – BEST PRACTICE)
✅ Most secure
✅ Works across tabs automatically
✅ Used in real production apps
How it works
	• Backend sets a session cookie or JWT cookie
	• Browser sends it automatically in every tab
	• On page load, frontend checks /me or /validate-session
Backend (example)
Set-Cookie: authToken=abc123; HttpOnly; Secure; SameSite=Lax
Frontend (React)

useEffect(() => {
  fetch("/api/me", { credentials: "include" })
    .then(res => res.ok ? res.json() : null)
    .then(user => {
      if (user) setUser(user);
    });
}, []);
✅ New tab = session still active

✅ 2. Use localStorage (Very Common)
✅ Simple
✅ Works across tabs
⚠ Less secure than cookies
Store token on login
localStorage.setItem("token", jwtToken);
Check auth on app load

useEffect(() => {
  const token = localStorage.getItem("token");

Protect routes

<Route
  path="/dashboard"
  element={isLoggedIn ? <Dashboard /> : <Navigate to="/login" />}
/>
✅ New tab reads same localStorage, so user stays logged in.

✅ 3. Use Redux + persistence
Useful if your app already uses Redux.
npm install redux-persist

import { persistReducer, persistStore } from "redux-persist";
import storage from "redux-persist/lib/storage";
✅ State survives refresh & new tabs.

✅ 4. Detect login/logout across tabs (optional but powerful)
If user logs out in one tab, auto‑logout in other tabs.

window.addEventListener("storage", (event) => {
  if (event.key === "token" && !event.newValue) {
    window.location.href = "/login";
  }
});

✅ Recommended Architecture (Real‑World)
App Type	Recommendation
Enterprise / Banking / SSO	✅ HTTP‑Only Cookies
Small / Internal tools	✅ LocalStorage
SPA with auth server	✅ Cookie + /me API
High security	✅ Cookie + Refresh Token

✅ Minimal Example (LocalStorage)

// App.jsx
function App() {
  const [isLoggedIn, setIsLoggedIn] = useState(false);
  useEffect(() => {
    const token = localStorage.getItem("token");
    setIsLoggedIn(!!token);
  }, []);
  return (
    <Routes>
      <Route path="/login" element={<Login />} />
      <Route
        path="/home"
        element={isLoggedIn ? <Home /> : <Navigate to="/login" />}
      />
    </Routes>
  );
}

🔴 What does NOT work
❌ useState only
❌ Context without persistence
❌ Redux without saving state
❌ Session stored in memory only
New tab = new JS process = state lost.

✅ Final Recommendation (For You)
✅ If your backend exists → use cookies
✅ If frontend‑only → use localStorage

